SIMPLE: interpellation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Interpellation
<hw>In`ter*pel*la"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>interpellatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>interpellation</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of interpelling or interrupting;
interruption.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Continual <xex>interpellations</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of interposing or interceding;
intercession.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Accepted by his <qex>interpellation</qex> and intercession.</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An act of interpellating, or of demanding of an
officer an explanation of his action; imperative or peremptory
questioning; a point raised in a debate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A official summons or citation.</def>
<rj><au>Ayliffe.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Interpenetrate</ent>⟦br⟧
